":"1248","1368":"1368","1277":"1277","1318":"1318","about 1274":"about 1274","Bolton, Lancashire, England":"Bolton, Lancashire, England, United Kingdom","Sharples Manor, Bolton, Lancashire, England, UK":"Bolton, Lancashire, England, United Kingdom","Sharples, Bolton, Lancashire, England":"Sharples, Lancashire, England, United Kingdom","Upholland, Lancashire, England":"Up Holland, Lancashire, England","Lancashire, England":"Lancashire, England","Sharples, Lancashire, England":"Sharples, Lancashire, England","England, United Kingdom":"England, United Kingdom","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Holland","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["English, German, Dutch, Danish, Norwegian, Swedish, French, and Jewish (Ashkenazic): habitational name from <i>Holland</i>, a province of the Netherlands.","English: habitational name from Downholland or Upholland (Lancashire), Hulland (Derbyshire), the Parts of Holland, one of the three administrative subdivisions of Lincolnshire, any of the four places called Hoyland (southern Yorkshire), and possibly Great and Little Holland (Essex). The placenames all derive from Old English <i>hōh</i> ‘heel, spur of land’ + <i>land</i> ‘land’.","English: habitational name either from Hoeland (Farm) in Bury (Sussex), or from Holland's Barn in Albourne (Sussex). The placename in Bury has the same etymology as in 1 above, while the placename in Albourne may derive from Old English <i>hol</i> ‘hole, hollow’ + <i>land</i> ‘land’."],"variants":[{"name":"Hollands","meanings":["English: variant of   Holland  , especially 3, with post-medieval excrescent <i>-s</i>.","Dutch: genitivized form of   Holland  ."]},{"name":"Howland","meanings":["English: variant of   Holland  .","Americanized form of Norwegian   Hovland  .","History: Howland was the name of three Quaker brothers, original settlers in Marshfield, MA. They were from Huntingdonshire, England. The eldest, John Howland (<i>c.</i> 1593–1672) was a passenger on the <i>Mayflower</i>, servant to Gov. John Carver, who died in the first winter at Plymouth Colony."]},{"name":"Hollander","meanings":["Dutch (also <b>Den Hollander</b>), German (also <b>Holländer</b>), English, Swedish, and Jewish (Ashkenazic): habitational name for someone from Holland (see   Holland   1)."]},{"name":"Holand","meanings":["English and Scottish: variant of   Holland  .","Norwegian: habitational name from about twenty farmsteads so named, composed of Old Norse <i>hár</i> ‘high’ + <i>land</i> ‘land, field’, denoting a high-lying farm."]},{"name":"Aland","meanings":["Scandinavian (<b>Åland</b>): topographic name from the Åland Islands in the Gulf of Bothnia.","English: topographic name from Middle English <i>atte lande</i> (Old French <i>laund</i>) ‘dweller at the glade or pasture’, or sometimes perhaps, ‘dweller at the old cultivated land(s)’ from Old English <i>eald</i>, <i>ald</i> ‘old’ + <i>land</i> ‘land’."]},{"name":"Hollon","meanings":["English: altered form of   Holland  ."]}]},{"name":"Sir","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["From Old Norse, originally a byname meaning ‘bride, wife’; in mythology the name of Thor's golden-haired wife."],"variants":[]},{"name":"William","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Probably the most successful of all the Old French names of Germanic origin that were introduced to England by the Normans. It is derived from Germanic <i>wil</i> ‘will, desire’ + <i>helm</i> ‘helmet, protection’. The fact that it was borne by the Conqueror himself does not seem to have inhibited its favour with the ‘conquered’ population: in the first century after the Conquest it was the commonest male name of all, and not only among the Normans. In the later Middle Ages it was overtaken by   John  , but continued to run second to that name until the 20th century, when the picture became more fragmented."],"variants":[]}],"lifeSummary":"When Sir William Holland was born in 1275, in Bolton, Lancashire, England, United Kingdom, his father, William de Holand of Sharples, was 28 and his mother, Joan de Latham, was -11. He married Margaret de Shoresworth in 1290, in Up Holland, Lancashire, England. They were the parents of at least 2 sons. He died in 1318, in his hometown, at the age of 43."},"et":{"1275–1318":"1275–1318","1274–Female":"1274–Surnud","1277–1349":"1277–1349","1270–1363":"1270–1363","1290–1368":"1290–1368","1292–Male":"1292–Surnud","1248–1314":"1248–1314","1286–Female":"1286–Surnud","abt 1292":"umbes 1292","1275":"1275","1286":"1286","1363":"1363","1274":"1274","1292":"1292","1270":"1270","1290":"1290","1349":"1349","1314":"1314","1248":"1248","1368":"1368","1277":"1277","1318":"1318","about 1274":"umbes 1274","Bolton, Lancashire, England":"Bolton, Lancashire, Inglismaa, United Kingdom","Sharples Manor, Bolton, Lancashire, England, UK":"Bolton, Lancashire, Inglismaa, United Kingdom","Sharples, Bolton, Lancashire, England":"Sharples, Lancashire, Inglismaa, United Kingdom","Upholland, Lancashire, England":"Up Holland, Lancashire, England","Lancashire, England":"Lancashire, England","Sharples, Lancashire, England":"Sharples, Lancashire, England","England, United Kingdom":"Inglismaa, United Kingdom"},"fi":{"1275–1318":"1275–1318","1274–Female":"1274–Kuollut","1277–1349":"1277–1349","1270–1363":"1270–1363","1290–1368":"1290–1368","1292–Male":"1292–Kuollut","1248–1314":"1248–1314","1286–Female":"1286–Kuollut","abt 1292":"noin 1292","1275":"1275","1286":"1286","1363":"1363","1274":"1274","1292":"1292","1270":"1270","1290":"1290","1349":"1349","1314":"1314","1248":"1248","1368":"1368","1277":"1277","1318":"1318","about 1274":"noin 1274","Bolton, Lancashire, England":"Bolton, Lancashire, Englanti, Yhdistynyt kuningaskunta","Sharples Manor, Bolton, Lancashire, England, UK":"Bolton, Lancashire, Englanti, Yhdistynyt